      <guid>http://localhost:1313/archive/puzzle-homefun/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;homefun&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;strong&gt;Homefun&lt;/strong&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#homefun&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Due: &lt;code&gt;February 3, 2025&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote class=&#34;book-hint warning&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Warning:&lt;/strong&gt; This page is under construction.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;book-tabs&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;input type=&#34;radio&#34; class=&#34;toggle&#34; name=&#34;tabs-1&#34; id=&#34;tabs-1-0&#34; checked=&#34;checked&#34; /&gt;&#xA;&lt;label for=&#34;tabs-1-0&#34;&gt;Logistics&lt;/label&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;book-tabs-content markdown-inner&#34;&gt;&lt;p&gt;This assignment is managed through a single Github classroom assignment. You can accept it via &#xA;  &lt;a href=&#34;https://classroom.github.com/a/-W652rH9&#34;&gt;this link&lt;/a&gt;. This will create a new repository that you have write access to. Once you accept it, &lt;strong&gt;read the &lt;code&gt;README&lt;/code&gt; file.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;When you push commits to this repository, an automatic testing job will run pre-written tests. These tests verify that your program produces the right outputs on certain inputs. You can find verbal descriptions of each one in the &amp;ldquo;Checks&amp;rdquo; section. Further, all of the tests&amp;rsquo; expected input/output pairs are publically visible in the autograder workflow runs.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Homefun Pt. 1</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/archive/game-homefun-p1/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/archive/game-homefun-p1/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;homefun-part-1&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;strong&gt;Homefun Part 1&lt;/strong&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#homefun-part-1&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Due: &lt;code&gt;11:59PM 9/11/2024&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;book-tabs&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;input type=&#34;radio&#34; class=&#34;toggle&#34; name=&#34;tabs-0&#34; id=&#34;tabs-0-0&#34; checked=&#34;checked&#34; /&gt;&#xA;&lt;label for=&#34;tabs-0-0&#34;&gt;Logistics&lt;/label&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;book-tabs-content markdown-inner&#34;&gt;&lt;p&gt;Both parts of the Homefun are managed through a single Github classroom assignment. You can accept it &#xA;  &lt;a href=&#34;https://classroom.github.com/a/-W652rH9&#34;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;. This will create a new repository that you have write access to. &lt;strong&gt;Read the &lt;code&gt;README&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt; When you push new commits on this repository, an &amp;ldquo;autograding&amp;rdquo; job will run the tests for both parts.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;These tests simply verify that your program has the correct outputs for certain inputs. Each part has a set of input/output pairs that the tests enforce. &lt;strong&gt;If the latest commit on your Homefun repository&amp;rsquo;s &lt;code&gt;main&lt;/code&gt; branch passes all of a given part&amp;rsquo;s tests before its due date passes, you will receive full credit for that part of the Homefun.&lt;/strong&gt; You can see which tests belong to which part in the assignments&amp;rsquo; &amp;ldquo;Checks&amp;rdquo; sections.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Homefun Pt. 1</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/main/assignments/game-homefun-p1/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/main/assignments/game-homefun-p1/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;homefun-part-1&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;strong&gt;Homefun Part 1&lt;/strong&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#homefun-part-1&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Due: &lt;code&gt;11:59PM 9/10/2025&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;summary&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Summary&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#summary&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Write a program that computes the strong solution of two related games, &lt;code&gt;10-to-0-by-1-or-2&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;25-to-0-by-1-3-or-4&lt;/code&gt;. Any programming language is acceptable. Optional aid is provided in the form of a &#xA;  &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/GamesCrafters/homefun&#34;&gt;Python template&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;game-representation&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Game Representation&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#game-representation&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The object of the Homefun series will be to find out specific facts about a certain class of games. It can be summarized as: &amp;ldquo;For games like Chess, Tic-Tac-Toe, and Connect-4, how do I put them into a computer and have it tell me how to play perfectly?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
